    <div class="annotation">
      <h3>Step Basics</h3>
      <p>The <strong>time</strong> of a step is an estimate of the nubmer of minutes it takes for the entire step to finish. This includes time when the cook is not actively doing anything. These times do not need to be exact, but should be a reasonable guess of the time it would take an average cook to complete this task. Other users will be able to customize these times later.</p>
      <p>A key component of Lattice meal schedules is ensuring that a cook's kitchen <strong>equipment</strong> is not overused. In order to do this, we need to know if a step uses a limited kitchen resource, like the oven. We assume, however, that a cook won't run out of knives, bowls, pots, etc. while completing basic cooking tasks.</p>
      <h4>Breaking Up Steps</h4>
      <p>Since Lattice meal schedules aim to optimize a cook's time and resources, it is critical that the steps in Lattice recipes are broken down into small, indivisible tasks. If a recipe's step contains multiple subactions, a Lattice meal schedule will be unable to schedule these actions at the same time or to schedule another action in between them.</p>
      <p>In general, a single step should not use more than one piece of equipment or use different amounts of attention. If the first part of a step uses some attention and the second part uses all attention, it should be split into separate steps.</p>
